The gear life. I've owned a lot of different gear in my relatively short career so far. I used to be obsessed with gear. But most of that obsession has worn off. While gear is an important part of my job, my mind is often on training standards. Gear is great. But skills are best. I've come to learn that gear is next to useless if you don't have the skills to take full advantage of said gear.
-
One reason gear is appealing to people is that it doesn't take a lot of skill to wear or own. But shooting skills.... takes a lot of work to develop and perfect. Which do you think is more important in the grand scheme of things?
-

Having standards is not having an endless list of requirements for your BF/GF/brother or friend. That’s called being high maintenance.
.
Having standards is about knowing yourself. Knowing what makes you tick in life, and the kind of person you want to be. It can take a little time to work out what those things are.
.
Setting personal standards – in relationships, at work and for your health – can make the difference between living life powerfully and feeling permanently stressed and uneasy.
.
For me, defining my standards has ended a lot of procrastination, conflict and frustration, and has enabled me to live a more purposeful life. You could say that having standards has made me consistently happier.
.
We all have a ‘behind-the-scenes’ set of rules governing our conduct and outlook. They are reflected in the quality of our relationships, our work and the way we communicate. We reveal our standards to people all the time!
.
If you haven’t actively created your standards – then where have they come from?
.
Standards are imposed on us from the outside from the day we are born.
.
They come from:
• Our parents.
• Our schooling/education.
• The media.
• Society.
• Culture.
.
Each of the above have had an influence on how we think we should look, feel, and be spending our time. The standards become unthinkingly intertwined in our mindsets.
.
Having clear #standards is like having an internal #validation system. It takes the focus away from any outside markers of success, putting them entirely in the province of the personal.
.
Knowing what’s important to your #happiness and fulfillment takes #procrastination out of the equation.
.
Defining yourself by reference to the standards you create is far more logical than defining yourself by your gender, background, or sexuality. Your standards and ideals are something you actually have control over and can exercise uniqueness with. © Rezzan Hussey
